The county has been consistent in registering inconsistent poll results for decades. Having been a teacher and a correspondent for one of the leading dailies based in region for a decade before pursuing other interests, Feisal’s victory, backed by Governor Salim Mvurya, against Mombasa Governor Hassan Joho’s Boga, did not surprise me.





Personality politics and revolt to interference from Mombasa leadership are not only major but also the underlying factors in this region dominated by the Digo, the Duruma and the ‘immigrant’ Kamba community. In 1997, a high school teacher, Marere wa Mwachai, pulled a surprise to become the first Mijikenda woman elected to Parliament owing to her sterling academic credentials against her main competitor, Kassim Mwamzandi.
In 2002, while President Mwai Kibaki’s Narc swept everywhere, Gonzi Rai made it in Kinango on a Ford-People ticket, leaving Narc’s LDP wing in Matuga and Msambweni through Chirau Ali Mwakwere and Juma Abdallah Ngozi.
 Shirikisho Party
Rai retained his seat on the same ticket in 2007, but Mwakwere won on a Shirikisho Party, leaving ODM in Msambweni to Omar Zonga, who had beaten Ngozi. Mwakwere lost his seat to the petitioner, Hassan Mwanyoha, in 2010, and in the ensuing by-election, with support of the then-Kisauni MP Hassan Joho, a storm brewed in Matuga. Mwakwere recaptured his seat on the then not popular Party of National Unity (PNU). The campaign had been very tough and Mwakwere was rattled till he allegedly got involved in hate speech. This got him to court but the charges were dropped.



